localStorage only saves data in strings which is why we JSON.stringify it first
java

localStorage.getItem gets the key's value
the value of localStorage.getItem by default is a string
JSON.parse is an automatic translator --> if the stringified value was orginally an array it will turn it into an array or it was originally an object it will turn it into an object


to save:
localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value of key));
if the value is already a string there is no need for JSON.stringify
Everything else must be converted


localStorage.deleteItem(key)
deletes only the values of the key

localStorage.clear()
deletes all data within the local storage
